04461nam a22005535i 9780774850483DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072003xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748504837 a10.59962/97807748504832doi  a(DE-B1597)661430  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE99.B39bM49 2003eb 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a971.1/100497900aAt Home with the Bella Coola Indians :bT.F. McIlwraith's Field Letters, 1922-4 /ced. by John Barker, Douglas Cole. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b15 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tThe Bella Coola Field Letters of T.F. McIlwraith 1922–4 -- tThe First Season, March to July 1922 -- tThe Second Season, September 1923 to March 1924 -- tBella Coola Manuscripts -- tAt Home with the Bella Coola Indians -- tCertain Aspects of the Potlatch among the Bella Coola -- tObservations on the Medical Lore of the Bella Coola Indians, British Columbia -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tSources and Permissions for Letters -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween 1922 and 1924, the young Canadian anthropologist T.F. McIlwraith spent eleven months in the isolated community of Bella Coola, British Columbia, living among the people of the Nuxalk First Nation. During his time there, McIlwraith gained intimate knowledge of the Nuxalk culture and of their struggle to survive in the face of massive depopulation, loss of traditional lands, and the efforts of the Canadian government to ban the potlatch. McIlwraith's resulting ethnography, The Bella Coola Indians (1948), is widely considered the finest published study of a Northwest Coast First Nation. This volume is a rich complement to McIlwraith's classic work, incorporating his letters from the field as well as previously unpublished essays on the Nuxalk. Vivid and lively, the letters show the human side of the anthropologist, and provide a fascinating insight into the famous Northwest winter ceremonials and potlatch -- events in which McIlwraith was one of the few white men privileged to participate as a dancer and partner. Extensive editorial annotations and striking photographs make this book a pleasurable read that will appeal to anthropologists and historians, as well as those with interests in Northwest cultures and the history of anthropology in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aBarker, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCole, Douglas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcIlwraith, T.F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcIlwraith, Thomas Forsyth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485048340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774850483423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774850483/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles